28ec9178-3317-46ee-9454-bf3d13e5a042.0194d304-8ee4-4cbd-b77a-e58de2398e6f.description=
Sorts a list. If this list is all numerical, it is sorted in numerical order, other wise it is sorted in alphabetical order.

Inputs\:
delimiter - The list delimiter.
list - The list to be processed
reverse - A boolean value, sort the list in reverse order?

Responses\:
success - The operation completed Successfully.
failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
The sorted list
28ec9178-3317-46ee-9454-bf3d13e5a042.13db606b-2c32-4b05-9fe6-04c7ce5809e2.description=
Performs a mathematical operation on two numbers or strings

Inputs\:
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.
operation - The operation to perform (+ - * ^ / > < \=\= \!\= >\= <\=).

Responses\:
success -  The operation completed successfully. If a boolean operation, it evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.

Returns\:
The raw result of the operation, for boolean values this is true or false.

Returns\:
Field 1 - The first value. Here for compatibility
Field 2 - The second value. Here for compatibility
Field 3 - The operation. Here for compatibility
formatted_result - The formatted result of the operation, for boolean values this is true or false.
28ec9178-3317-46ee-9454-bf3d13e5a042.288878aa-66ce-4bd9-b831-95a7d8a80e3c.description=
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable.

Returns\: 
The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable.

Responses\:
isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned.
28ec9178-3317-46ee-9454-bf3d13e5a042.6ad21da3-fd24-4646-af80-b9eca0b07681.description=
Adds a flow variable into the local context (available to itself and child flows only)

Input Parameters\:
keyName - the name of the flow variable to use
myValue - the value to assign the flow variable

Responses\:
success - assigned the flow variable

Scriptlet Example\:
[$scriptletContext putGlobal\: $keyName, $myValue];
28ec9178-3317-46ee-9454-bf3d13e5a042.922dd85a-e01f-4331-8c16-ca4b22355185.description=
Retrieves a value from a list.

Inputs\:
delimiter - The list delimiter.
list - The list to be processed
index - The index (starting at 0) of the value to read from the list.

Responses\:
success - The operation completed Successfully.
failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
The value read from the list.

28ec9178-3317-46ee-9454-bf3d13e5a042.description=
Synopsis

    This flow generates a LIF interface name based on the cluster name and vLAN ID.
    generateLifInterfaceName performs the following steps\:
      1. Retireve a list of LIFs.
      2. Iterate through and transform the list of LIFs into an xslt document.
      3. If a name does not already exist, sort the list by index number.
      4. Iterate through and separate the list based on a net index number of either less than or greater than nine.
      5. Pass the LIF interface name to the requesting entity.

Inputs

    clusterName - The IP or host name of the NetApp cluster.
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or RFC 1123 compliant host name.
      Default value\: None.

    vlanId - The name of the vLan used in the flow.
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.	
      Default value\: None.

    overrideJRAS - Value to override the system defined Java RAS server.
      Valid values\: Implementation specific.
      Default value\: Hosting Eng RAS.

Results

    hpooFlowResult - The XML response specific to the functionality of the flow;  in this case, a LIF interface name is returned.  See Notes section for more details.
    flowStatus - Overall status of the flow, value is one of the string literals "success" or "failed".

Responses

    Success - All operations and subflows completed successfully.
    Failure - Some operations and/or subflows failed. 

Notes

    1. Anything else the caller or support person may need to know about the flow. Relationships that aren't easily inferred, abmnormal flow behaviors, hard-codings, etc.

<?xml version="1.0"?>
<xsl:stylesheet version="1.0" xmlns:xsl="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform" xmlns:xslt="http://xml.apache.org/xslt" exclude-result-prefixes="xslt"> <xsl:output method="text" />
<xsl:template match="results"> <xsl:for-each select="attributes-list/net-interface-info"> <xsl:if test="string-length(address/text()) > 0 and starts-with(interface-name/text(), 'd_${vlanId}_')"> <xsl:value-of select="interface-name/text()"/> <xsl:if test="not(position() = last())"> <xsl:text> </xsl:text> </xsl:if> </xsl:if> </xsl:for-each> </xsl:template>
</xsl:stylesheet>
